42. Nearly all the plays of Plautus open with lambio senoni. This is the verse of ordinary narrative or dia logne, sometimes also of soliloquy, and seems the one best adopted for making the audience acquainted with the general situation. Its movement may be illustrated by the following lines:-

“The tempest nears us; darkly rolls the angry sea; The thunder mutters; lightnings leap from cloud to cloud.”

As the plot develops, the metre changes to suit the varying moods of the characters.
